e of those captured letters.\nChristmas of 11*42 arrived. W<\nmade the best of what we had in\nSanto Tomas and a few of us even\ngave presents to our closest\nfvi^vds. We tried to lie cheerful,\nthinking that it was tin* last cele\nbration of this type we'd spend in\ncaptivity. But we faced even hard\ner times just a year later with little\nfood, few clothes, and again being\nrelief\n\nmost certain that the end of our\nlong confinement was no where in\nsight.\nThe latter part of 11*42 was in\ndeed a time of great rejoicing for\nns because it was at this time our\nfirst American Red Gross\nsupplies came through. Those wer\u00bb\nour first kits to arrive\nothers were never allowed to reach\nus. It was worth every effort of\nthe Red Gross to make any attempt\nto see that tilings reached ns lie\ncause this one vast supply un\ndoubtedly saved the lives of hun\ndreds of us.\nWhen life hung much in the bal\nance for ns. Christmas of 11*44, and\nevery internee was putting forth\nhis greatest effort to keep living.\nAmerican planes flew over our camp\nand dropped the most wonderful\nChristmas message to us anyone\ncould ever hope to receive:\n\"The C'ommaiider-in-Chief. Offi\ncers and the Men of the American\nForces of Liberation in the Pacific\nwish their gallant allies. Hie peo\nple of the Philippines, all flu* bles\nsings of Christmas and the reali\nzation of their fervent hopes of the\nNew Year.\" Christmas, Bill.\nand all\n\nPhis message.-like all eommuni\ncations dropped to us. infuriated\ntlie Jap commandant and ids staff,\nImmediately lie gave orders to all\nguards to gather up any pamphlets.\nShould any more tome into camp.\nwere to take them directly to\nhis office. His warning\ntoo late. Those who had received\nthese messages kept them and from\nthe original copies most everyone\nin our camp made a copy for him\nself, tucking it away where il\nwe\ncame much\nease of a\nsudden search by the Japanese.\nChristmas of last year found ev\neryone cooking Hie best we had\nfor dinner that day. I joined three\nfriends who assisted me in making\nour meager meal for that day\nmeal which to us who were starv\ning. seemed better than any least\nof steak or chicken. It was food\ndoctored up into famous Santo To\nmas recipes. Here is what our din\nner consisted of:\nMeat loaf, made of canned eorn\netl beef, rice, meal and\na\nca ssava\nflour. To make rice Hour. 1 put the\nrice kernels into a sack and heat\nthem on Hie stone step,\nthought for sure I had\nhack into the Stone Age. (im\nplements and way of working\nso crude.\nreverted\nReally 1\nwere\ncans ot\n\neo n kind onI f a U'W had Bun\nt a kind ot vegetable shortening.\nOthers were trying to fry pan cakes\nwith no lard to grease the pan.\nmille a y vcgl\nfable that grew in our camp gar\n'vm/v S T eth V lg i\"\"-* apiuat,h\nNative coffee\u2014I made it by roast\na eie ,f n c P f ee beans and at\nteivvaids chopping these in a hag\nbefore boiling for coffee. Needless\nto say this drink was stimulating\neven though it gave us indigestion\nafteivvaids.\nBiscuits made from all mixtures\nof the last of any of our flour and\nbaked in a native oven over a I\n.small charcoal (ire.\nim\nGravy made from small\nham and eggs, thickened with dark\ncassava flour, and flavored with\nplenty of garlic.\nFried rice\n1\nI\nI'aptain Robert 11.\nsou of Mr, and Mrs, {Cohort\nSmith, of Han ington.\nanions tip* group of oflioor rt*|daoi*\nmonts that doharkod from\ntransport which\non November 21. His\nManila. I*. I,\nSmith.\nit.\nwas\nan army\nlooked in Manila\nFirst assign\nment on tho Islands was to the 24th\nReplacement Depot which is locat\ned in Pampanga Province, tin miles\nnorth of Manila on the Island of\nHe is here at the\n\nntzon.\npresent\ntime awaiting an assignment to re\nplace a high point\nwho has been returned to the Uni\nted States\naptain\narmy career at\nBaltimore in 1!\u00bbI2. He attended the\nservice school in Carlisle.\nPa., and was then assigned to the\ndental clinic at Camp Ellis. III. S